Northern Development:
Those with a stake in the Mining Industry should await with interest the outcome of the
latest State-Commonwealth Conference on Northern Development.
Of special significance is the fact that this first series of talks held outside Canberra took
place in Queensland and included an on-the-spot inspection of mineral developments in the
Central Division of the State.
It is vitally important that the three Governments with a special interest in northern
development-Queensland, Western Australia and the Commonwealth-should have first hand
knowledge of each other's special problems and existing and projected developments.
It seems obvious that in the final analysis, northern development will have to be co-ordin-
ated at every level, and a proper understanding of what is involved is a first essential to eventual
success.
If we are to accelerate development in the north, all three Governments will have to grasp
and appreciate each other's special problems SO that future expenditure can be utilised in the
most advantageous way.
The north is a big place and it is going to require big thinking to fully utilise all its natural
resources.
Mining is destined to play an ever increasing role in the future of the north and under-
standably, mining is interested in what is going on.
Mining has already demonstrated in all three northern spheres of political influence that
scope for development is almost unlimited. The same is true for the pastoral and agricultural
industries.
Today, Northern Development is a fact, tomorrow it could well be a prerequisite of our
very survival.

Geological surveys soon made it clear that the ore de-
posits in the western portion of the Weipa peninsula held
larger quantities of higher grade ore than those adjacent to
other possible port sites. This led to the Evans Landing
site being chosen as the most suitable for preliminary port
development and the adjacent Lorim Point became the site in
turn for permanent plant facilities and shiploading.

fluence of waves were simulated to provide data that deter-
mined the best location and alignment of what became the
dredged South Channel, running close in past Urquhart Point.
